Motivation

Extension of Holtâs Method to capture seasonality. It comprises the forecast equation and three smoothing equations for the following paramentrs

  • The level \(l_t\) (parameter \(\alpha\))
  • The trend \(b_t\) (parameter \(\beta*\))
  • The seasonal component \(s_t\) (parameter \(\gamma\))

The symbol \(m\) is the length of the seasonality period, i.e., the duration of seasons a seasonal period. For quarterly data \(m = 4\), for monthly data \(m= 12\), etcâ¦ etcâ¦

Additive vs Multiplicative:

There are two variations of the method.

  • The additive method is preferred when the seasonal variations do not change proportionally to the level of the series.
    • Seasonal component expressed in absolute terms in the scale of the observed series
    • Level equation: the series is seasonally adjusted by subtracting the seasonal component
    • Within a year the seasonal component will add up to approximately zero (for further details see the lessons on classical decomposition).
  • The multiplicative method is preferred when the seasonal variations change proportionally to the level of the series.
    • Seasonal component expressed in relative terms (percentages)
    • Level equation: the series is seasonally adjusted by dividing through by the seasonal component.
    • Within a year the seasonal component will sum up to approximately \(m\).

Holtâs Wintersâ additive method:

Component form equations:

\[\begin{align*} \hat{y}_{t+h|t} &= \ell_{t} + hb_{t} + s_{t+h-m(k+1)} \\ \ell_{t} &= \alpha(y_{t} - s_{t-m}) + (1 - \alpha)(\ell_{t-1} + b_{t-1})\\ b_{t} &= \beta^*(\ell_{t} - \ell_{t-1}) + (1 - \beta^*)b_{t-1}\\ s_{t} &= \gamma (y_{t}-\ell_{t-1}-b_{t-1}) + (1-\gamma)s_{t-m}, \end{align*}\]

The index \(k = int(\frac{h-1}{m})\) might be confusing. \(int()\) is the function integer part. In other words, \(k\) is the number of periods between the current forecast horizon \(h\) and the latest available observation.

  • when computing fitted values \(h = 1\) (one-step ahead forecasts on the training data). Therefore \(k = 0\) when computing the fitted values. This results in a summand \(s_{t+1-m}\) on the level equation when computing fitted values, indicating that the seasonal component is borrowed from the previous seasonal period. The resulting equation for fitted values:
\[\begin{align*} \hat{y}_{t+1|t} &= \ell_{t} + b_{t} + s_{t+1-m} \\ \end{align*}\]
  • when computing forecasts:
    • for the first season (\(1 \leq h \leq m\)) we have \(\frac{h-1}{m} < 1\) and thus \(k = 0\).
    • for later seasons (\(m+1 \leq h\) we have \(\frac{h-1}{m} \geq 1\)) and thus \(k \geq 1\).
    • Thus the index \(k\) ensures that the estimates of the seasonal component used for forecasting are the seasonal estimates of the last season of training data. We will understand this further when doing a simple example.

Let us briefly interpret the equations:

  • The forecast equation: shows that the h-step ahead forecast is equal to the last estimated level \(l_t\) plus h times the last estimated trend \(b_t\) value plus the value of the seasonal component corresponding to the last estimated season \(s_{t+h-m(k+1)}\):
\[\begin{align*} \hat{y}_{t+h|t} &= \ell_{t} + hb_{t} + s_{t+h-m(k+1)} \end{align*}\]
  • Level equation: weighted average between the seasonally adjusted observation and the non-seasonal forecast
\[\begin{align*} l_{t} &= \alpha\underbrace{(y_{t} - s_{t-m})}_\textrm{seasonally adjusted observation} + (1 - \alpha)\underbrace{(\ell_{t-1} + b_{t-1})}_\textrm{non seasonal forecast}\\ \end{align*}\]
  • Trend equation: identical to Holtâs linear method.
\[\begin{align*} \text{Trend equation} && b_{t} &= \underbrace{\beta^*(\ell_{t} - \ell_{t-1})}_\textrm{estimated trend at time t} + \underbrace{(1 -\beta^*)b_{t-1}}_\textrm{previous estimate of the trend}, \end{align*}\]
  • The seasonal equation: weighted average between the current seasonal index and the seasonal index of the same observation for last year (\(m\) periods ago)
\[\begin{align*} s_{t} &= \underbrace{\gamma (y_{t}-\ell_{t-1}-b_{t-1})}_\textrm{current seasonal index} + \underbrace{(1-\gamma)s_{t-m}}_\textrm{seasonal index of the same season, last year} \end{align*}\]

Holt Winterâs multiplicative Method:

The component form of the multiplicative method is:

\[\begin{align*} \hat{y}_{t+h|t} &= (\ell_{t} + hb_{t})s_{t+h-m(k+1)} \\ \ell_{t} &= \alpha \frac{y_{t}}{s_{t-m}} + (1 - \alpha)(\ell_{t-1} + b_{t-1})\\ b_{t} &= \beta^*(\ell_{t}-\ell_{t-1}) + (1 - \beta^*)b_{t-1} \\ s_{t} &= \gamma \frac{y_{t}}{(\ell_{t-1} + b_{t-1})} + (1 - \gamma)s_{t-m}. \end{align*}\]

The difference with the additive method is that the adjusted seasonal component is computed by dividing the observations by the seasonal component rather than by their difference.

Example: Domestic overnight trips in Australia

# Filter data
aus_holidays <- tourism %>%
  filter(Purpose == "Holiday") %>%
  summarise(Trips = sum(Trips)/1e3)

# Fit the models: additive and multiplicative seasonality
fit <- aus_holidays %>%
  model(
    additive = ETS(Trips ~ error("A") + trend("A") +
                                                season("A")),
    multiplicative = ETS(Trips ~ error("M") + trend("A") +
                                                season("M"))
  )

# Generate forecasts
fc <- fit %>% forecast(h = "3 years")

# Plot the forecasts
fc %>%
  autoplot(aus_holidays, level = NULL) +
  labs(title="Australian domestic tourism",
       y="Overnight trips (millions)") +
  guides(colour = guide_legend(title = "Forecast"))

fit %>% accuracy() %>% select(.model, RMSE) %>% mutate(RMSE = round(RMSE, 4))
# A tibble: 2 Ã 2
  .model          RMSE
  <chr>          <dbl>
1 additive       0.417
2 multiplicative 0.412

In this case the multiplicative scheme seems to fit the data slightly better, although the difference is not substantial.

These models already have a substantial number of parameters! This is because the models require a lot of initial estimates, that in the end are also a parameter. In summary we have

  • 3 smoothing parameters \(\alpha\), \(\beta*\) and \(\gamma\).
  • 6 initial estimates! (1 for the level \(l_0\), one for the trend \(b_0\) and 4 for the seasonal comonent \(s_{-3}, s_{-2}, ..., s_{0}\). If the data were monthly we would require 12 estimates. For longer seasonal periods (e.g.Â weekly data and yearly seasonality) the problem becomes substantially complex!

Recall the famous quote by the great mathematician John von Neumann:

âWith four parameters I can fit an elephant and with five I can make it wiggle his trunkâ (John von Neuman, cited by Enrico Fermi in Nature 427).

Fitting the models

Fitting these models requires an iterative process very similar to that outlined for trended methods in the previous session (the difference being that now there is an additional equation and smoothing parameter for the seasonal component):

In the table below, Holt-Wintersâ method with additive seasonality is developed in more detail. For that, the following initial values are required:

  • The level \(l_t\) of the series - estimated as the average of the observations in the first period (first four observations)
  • The slope of the series \(b_t\) - since the series send to have no trend within the first season, we estimate it as 0.
  • Estimates of the first 4 seasonal components - in this case we may take them as the first four elements of the seasonal component of a classical decomposition (additive) of the series. Note that for monthly data we would require 12 estimates. With longer seasonal periods this becaomes increasingly complex.

Holt-Winters damped method

This is often the singlemost accurate method for seasonal data. Often the variant with a damped trend and multiplicative seasonality works very well:

\[\begin{align*} \hat{y}_{t+h|t} &= \left[\ell_{t} + (\phi+\phi^2 + \dots + \phi^{h})b_{t}\right]s_{t+h-m(k+1)} \\ \ell_{t} &= \alpha(y_{t} / s_{t-m}) + (1 - \alpha)(\ell_{t-1} + \phi b_{t-1})\\ b_{t} &= \beta^*(\ell_{t} - \ell_{t-1}) + (1 - \beta^*)\phi b_{t-1} \\ s_{t} &= \gamma \frac{y_{t}}{(\ell_{t-1} + \phi b_{t-1})} + (1 - \gamma)s_{t-m}. \end{align*}\]

Example: daily data

Holt-Winters method can be used for daily type of data.

  • m = 7 (seasonal period, 1 week)
sth_cross_ped <- pedestrian %>%
  filter(Date >= "2016-07-01",
         Sensor == "Southern Cross Station") %>%
  index_by(Date) %>%
  summarise(Count = sum(Count)/1000)

sth_cross_ped

fit <- sth_cross_ped %>%
  filter(Date <= "2016-07-31") %>%
  model(
    hw = ETS(Count ~ error("M") + trend("Ad") + season("M"))
  ) 

fc <- fit %>%
  forecast(h = "2 weeks")

fc %>% 
  autoplot(sth_cross_ped %>% filter(Date <= "2016-08-14")) +
  labs(title = "Daily traffic: Southern Cross",
       y="Pedestrians ('000)")

The model has identified the weekly seasonal pattern and the increasing trend at the end of the data, and the forecasts are a close match to the test data.
